'''Thomas Wilkins''' (1625 or 1626 &ndash; 20 August 1699) was a Welsh cleric and antiquarian, who collected Welsh manuscripts.

==Life==
His father and his grandfather were both called Thomas Wilkins; all three in turn were [[rector (ecclesiastical)|rector]]s of St Mary's Church in [[Glamorgan]].  Wilkins (the grandson) was educated at [[Jesus College, Oxford]], [[matriculation|matriculating]] in 1641 and obtaining a law degree in 1661. He was rector of [[Gelligaer]] and [[Llan-maes]], and a [[prebendary]] of [[Llandaff Cathedral|Llandaff]].  In addition to his clerical duties, Wilkins was also an [[antiquarian]] and collected manuscripts, including the [[Red Book of Hergest]] and the [[Book of the Anchorite]].  After his death, on 20 August 1699, his eldest son (also called Thomas) donated these two manuscripts to Jesus College.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wilkins |url=http://wbo.llgc.org.uk/en/s-WILK-INS-1350.html|last=Thomas|first=Richard|work=Welsh Biography Online|publisher=[[National Library of Wales]]|accessdate=6 November 2008}}</ref>

